## Blood Flow Monitoring: 
The absorption and heating effects of mmWaves can be used to monitor blood flow non-invasively. A controlled amount of mmWave energy heats the skin, and the rate at which the skin cools is related to the blood flow, which carries heat away from the area. 

## dipole imaging
## Chirped-pulse Fourier transform (CP-FT) spectroscopy:
 This technique rapidly sweeps a broadband linear frequency across a gas sample.
How it works: A short, broadband millimeter-wave pulse polarizes the gas sample, causing it to emit a
## free induction decay (FID) signal.
 The FID is then Fourier transformed to produce a broadband frequency spectrum.
Advantages: It offers significantly faster spectral acquisition speeds (tens of GHz in microseconds) compared to traditional stepped-frequency methods, which can take several seconds per scan point.
## Direct digital synthesis (DDS) with frequency multiplication:
 This approach uses a highly stable DDS signal, up-converted into the mmWave band.
How it works: The DDS source functions as both a fast, switchable radiation source and a local oscillator for a sensitive heterodyne receiver. This setup allows for rapid frequency changes and long-term data averaging to enhance sensitivity.
## Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) processing: 
Advanced systems can use direct digitization of mmWave signals and FFT to achieve high temporal resolution and near real-time data processing.
Advantages: This provides high-resolution spectra at high speeds, with tested rates of up to 200,000 spectra per second, making it suitable for analyzing dynamic phenomena

