### Deep Learning (DL)
 DL has emerged as a powerful tool for super-resolution across many domains, including microwave imaging.
### Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) 
is trained on a dataset of low-resolution (LR) and high-resolution (HR) image pairs. The network learns the mapping from LR to HR, allowing it to generate super-resolved images from new LR inputs.
### SR enhancement:
 This data-driven approach can be used to improve the output of conventional SAR or other microwave imaging techniques, effectively boosting resolution in a variety of imaging dimensions. 
### Near-field enhancement
 This technique exploits the non-propagating evanescent waves that exist close to an object's surface. These waves contain high-frequency information that is lost in the far-field due to the diffraction limit.
### Method: 
For K-band imaging, this involves placing a receiver array or scanning probe very close to the object. Novel approaches use metasurfaces or structured illumination to convert evanescent waves into propagating ones that can be detected in the far-field.
## SR enhancement:
 By capturing this higher-frequency information, near-field methods can bypass the diffraction limit to achieve sub-wavelength resolution.
### Time-domain and spectral processing
 Some methods exploit the signal's bandwidth in the time or frequency domains to enhance resolution.
### Zero-Padding Pseudo-Pulse Algorithm (ZPPA) 
use computational manipulation of spectral data to improve range (depth) resolution. By extending the frequency spectrum with zero-padding before an inverse Fourier transform, finer details can be resolved in the time domain.
### SR enhancement:
 Broadband signals offer more information, and techniques that effectively process this information, like **ZPPA** or spectral shifting, can yield super-resolution beyond the limits of monochromatic imaging.



 
